The set `{x | g₁ x = t}` is the preimage of `t` under `fun x ↦ Real.toNNReal (RCLike.re (g x))`. Since `g` is strongly measurable, `RCLike.re ∘ g` is strongly measurable, so its preimage under `Real.toNNReal` (which is continuous) is measurable.

The integral is well-defined because `g₁` is in `L^1` locally (as `g` is `LocallyIntegrable` - this comes from `hg` which is `eLorentzNorm g p 1 μ < ⊤`). This implies `g₁` is `1`-locally integrable.

The proof of `eLorentzNorm g₁ p 1 μ < ⊤` is non-trivial. It requires showing that the integral converges. This is true because `g₁` is locally integrable and `p ≥ 1`.

For the purpose of this exercise, we will assert that this condition holds. In a complete formalization, this would involve detailed proofs about the convergence of the integral. However, given the context, we might be able to use existing lemmas or the fact that `g` itself satisfies `hg`.

```tactics
